"Bera P.P., Francisco J.S., Lee T.J.","Identifying the molecular origin of global warming",2009,"Journal of Physical Chemistry A","113","45",,"12694","12699",,,10.1021/jp905097g,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-70449376955&partnerID=40&md5=8cacad5b081d5e3af6bf7e570b5ca791","NASA Ames Research Center, Space Science and Astrobiology Division, Moffett Field, CA 94035, United States; Department of Earth and Atmospheric Sciences, Purdue University, West Lafayette, IN 47907-1393, United States; MS245-6, United States","Bera, P.P., NASA Ames Research Center, Space Science and Astrobiology Division, Moffett Field, CA 94035, United States, MS245-6, United States; Francisco, J.S., Department of Earth and Atmospheric Sciences, Purdue University, West Lafayette, IN 47907-1393, United States; Lee, T.J., NASA Ames Research Center, Space Science and Astrobiology Division, Moffett Field, CA 94035, United States, MS245-6, United States","We have investigated the physical characteristics of greenhouse gases (GHGs) to assess which properties are most important in determining the efficiency of a GHG. Chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs), hydrofluorocarbons (HFCs), perfluorocarbons (PFCs), nitrogen fluorides, and various other known atmospheric trace molecules have been included in this study. Compounds containing the halogens F or Cl have in common very polar X-F or X-Cl bonds, particularly the X-F bonds. It is shown that as more F atoms bond to the same central atom the bond dipoles become larger as a result of the central atom becoming more positive. This leads to a linear increase in the total or integrated X-F bond dipóle derivatives for the molecule, which leads to a nonlinear (quadratic) increase in infrared (IR) intensity. Moreover, virtually all of the X-F bond stretches occur in the atmospheric IR window as opposed to X-H stretches, which do not occur in the atmospheric window. It is concluded that molecules possessing several F atoms will always have a large radiative forcing parameter in the calculation of their global warming potential. Some of the implications for global warming and climate change are discussed. © 2009 American Chemical Society.",,"Atmospheric traces; Atmospheric window; Bond dipoles; Central atom; Global warming potential; Hydrofluorocarbons; IR window; Molecular origins; Perfluorocarbons; Physical characteristics; Radiative forcings; Atoms; Chlorine compounds; Chlorofluorocarbons; Fluorine compounds; Greenhouse gases; Inductively coupled plasma; Molecules; Windows; Global warming; fluoride; fluorocarbon; nitrogen; article; atmosphere; chemistry; climate; greenhouse effect; Atmosphere; Climate; Fluorides; Fluorocarbons; Global Warming; Nitrogen",,"fluoride, 16984-48-8; fluorocarbon, 11072-16-5; nitrogen, 7727-37-9; Fluorides; Fluorocarbons; Nitrogen, 7727-37-9",,,,"Wuebbles, D.J., Hayhoe, K., (2002) Earth-Sci. Rev., 57, p. 177; Forster, P., Ramaswamy, V., Artaxo, P., Berntsen, T., Betts, R., Fahey, D.W., Haywood, J., Schulz, M., Changes in Atmospheric Constituents and in Radiative Forcing (2007) Climate Change 2007: the Physical Science Basis. Contribution of Working Group i to the Fourth Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, , Solomon, S., Qin, D., Manning, M., Chen, Z., Marquis, M., Averyt, K. B. M. T., Miler, H. L., Eds.; Cambridge University Press: Cambridge, United Kingdom and New York, NY, USA; Shindel, D.T., Faluvegi, G., Bell, N., Schmidt, G.A.F.L., (2005) Geophys. Res. Lett., 32, pp. L04803; Bateman, E.J., Baggs, E., (2005) Biol. Fértil Soils, 41, p. 371; Shine, K.P., Stages, W.T., (2007) Science, 375, p. 1804; Spence, R.K., (1995) Artif Cells. Blood Substitutes Immobilization Biotechnol, 23, p. 367; Hassoun, S., McBride, T., Russel, D.A., (2000) J. Environ. Monit., 2, p. 432; White, C.M., Strazisar, B.R., Granite, E.J., Hoffman, J.S., Pennline, H.W., (2003) J. Air Waste Manage. Assoc., 53, p. 645; Watson, T.B., Wilke, R., Dietz, R.N., Heiser, J., Kalb, P., (2007) Envi